The stone is dirty.
The entire building slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling to the ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the most westward passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a delay in the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railroad running to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
