The fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurers often refuse to enter into an insurance contract on the basis of personal data on the purchase of medicinal products.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program that the use of prescription data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the medicines.
Insurance companies are subject to the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims to the health status of the customer and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not enter the insurance.
Time ago the client had to go on a medical visit and the contract was only concluded after the outcome of the exam.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the client's identification code you can easily get information from the pharmacies on which medicine you purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program evidence of what diseases you suffer and in what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is practically incorruptably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the programme, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not remain much in addition to paper work, even if there are small difficulties.
In contrast, some medicines can be used for more than one purpose, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraine or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, is worth as a risk increase factor, the first two are not.
In order to request and process data, companies have formed apart and these, before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities now oblige them to do so even if they have not yet imposed any fines on negligence.
Some companies have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients' state of health.
More and more companies have access to the data and at the same time the control of the use will be more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to the specialized enterprises in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the other data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot so much refuse approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
Then at the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
